actitioners alike. They show how this innovative but still amorphous movement can become more coherent, both on the ground and in public policy: reforming community development, building new kinds of neighbourhood partnership, measuring outcomes objectively, and combining the best innovations of the past three decades into a new synthesis. This is an important new perspective for all local public service agencies, all practitioners working in communities, and academics and students concerned with these fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCommunity developmentzGreat Britain. 0aCommunity organization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aMiller, Colin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTwelvetrees, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144730009040uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447314349?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447314349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447314349/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013